ncer|The Viscount Althorp]]}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[List of senior members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Senior Privy Counsellor]]\n | years  = 1906\u20131910\n | with   = [[Henry Reynolds-Moreton, 3rd Earl of Ducie|The Earl of Ducie]]\n | before = [[John Manners, 7th Duke of Rutland|The Duke of Rutland]]\n | after  = [[Henry Reynolds-Moreton, 3rd Earl of Ducie|The Earl of Ducie]]}}\n{{s-reg|gb}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Frederick Spencer, 4th Earl Spencer|Frederick Spencer]] | title=[[Earl Spencer (peerage)|Earl Spencer]] | years=1857\u20131910 | after=[[Charles Spencer, 6th Earl Spencer|Charles Spencer]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Leaders of the Opposition UK}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spencer, John Poyntz Spencer, 5th Earl}}\n[[Category:Spencer-Churchill family|John Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer]]\n[[Category:Earls Spencer| 05]]\n[[Category:First Lords of the Admiralty]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies|Althorp, John Spencer, Viscount]]\n[[Category:Lord-Lieutenants of Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:Lord Presidents of the Council]]\n[[Category:Lords Lieutenant of Ireland]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1857\u20131859|Althorp, John Spencer, Viscount]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Girls' Day School Trust]]\n[[Category:Members of Northamptonshire County Council]]\n[[Category:1835 births]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrow School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Marylebone Cricket Club]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Grooms of the Stool]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Earl Spencer \n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of the Garter|KG]] [[Order of St Patrick|KP]] [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]]\n| image = 5th earl spencer.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| caption = Lord Spencer.\n| order1 = [[Lord President of the Council]]\n| term_start1 = 28 April 1880\n| term_end1 = 19 March 1883\n| monarch1 = [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]]\n| primeminister1 = [[William Ewart Gladstone]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Charles Gordon-Lennox, 6th Duke of Richmond|The Duke of Richmond]]\n| successor1 = [[Chichester Parkinson-Fortescue, 1st Baron Carlingford|The Lord Carlingford]]\n| term_start2 = 6 February\n| term_end2 = 3 August 1886\n| monarch2 = [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]]\n| primeminister2 = [[William Ewart Gladstone]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Gathorne Gathorne-Hardy, 1st Earl of Cranbrook|The Viscount Cranbrook]]\n| successor2 = [[Gathorne Gathorne-Hardy, 1st Earl of Cranbrook|The Viscount Cranbrook]]\n| order3 = [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]]\n| term_start3 = 18 December 1868 \n| term_end3 = 17 February 1874\n| monarch3 = [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]]\n| primeminister3 = [[William Ewart Gladstone]]\n| predecessor3 = [[James Hamilton, 1st Duke of Abercorn|The Duke of Abercorn]]\n| successor3 = [[James Hamilton, 1st Duke of Abercorn|The Duke of Abercorn]]\n| term_start4 = 4 May 1882\n| term_end4 = 9 June 1885\n| monarch4 = [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]]\n| primeminister4 = [[William Ewart Gladstone]]\n| predecessor4 = [[Francis Cowper, 7th Earl Cowper|The Earl Cowper]]\n| successor4 = [[Henry Herbert, 4th Earl of Carnarvon|The Earl of Carnarvon]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1835|10|27}} \n| birth_place = [[Spencer House (St. James's, London, England)|Spencer House]], London \n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1910|08|13|1835|10|27}} \n| death_place = [[Althorp]], [[Northamptonshire]] \n| nationality = British\n| party = [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]]  \n| alma_mater = [[Trinity College, Cambridge]] \n| spouse = [[Charlotte Spencer, Countess Spencer|Charlotte Seymour]] (m. 1858\u20131903; her death)\n| Parents = {{plainlist|\n* [[Frederick Spencer, 4th Earl Spencer]]\n* Georgiana Poyntz\n}}\n}}\n'''John Poyntz Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer''', [[Order of the Garter|KG]], [[Order of St Patrick|KP]], [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] (27 October 1835 \u2013 13 August 1910), known as '''Viscount Althorp''' from 1845 to 1857 (and also known as the ''Red Earl'' because of his distinctive long red beard), was a British [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician under, and close friend of, British prime minister [[William Ewart Gladstone]]. He was twice [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]].\n\n==Background and education==\nSpencer was the son of [[Frederick Spencer, 4th Earl Spencer]], by his first wife Georgiana, daughter of William Poyntz. The prominent Whig politician [[John Spencer, 3rd Earl Spencer]], was his uncle and [[Charles Spencer, 6th Earl Spencer]], his half-brother. He was educated at [[Harrow School|Harrow]] and [[Trinity College, Cambridge]], from which he graduated in 1857.<ref>{{acad|id=SPNR853JP|name=Spencer, John Poyntz, Viscount Althorp}}</ref>\n\n==Political career, 1857\u20131885==\nAlmost immediately after leaving Cambridge Spencer was elected to parliament for [[South Northamptonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Northamptonshire]] as a Liberal, before departing for a tour of North America. He returned in December 1857, and within a few days his father died, leaving him as the new Earl Spencer. He was sworn of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in 1859<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=22283 |date=8 July 1859|page=2628}}</ref> and made a [[Order of the Garter|Knight of the Garter]] in 1864. Spencer split from other whiggish aristocratic Liberals in 1866 on the issue of [[John Russell, 1st Earl Russell|Russell]]'s reform bill, which he supported, and his loyalty was rewarded by his appointment as [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]] when Gladstone returned to power in 1868. Ireland came to be a major preoccupation of the remainder of Spencer's long political career. In this first tenure as Lord Lieutenant, he had to deal with implementation of the [[Irish Church Act 1869|disestablishment]] of the [[Church of Ireland]] in 1869 and of the [[Irish Land Act]] of 1870, both of which measures he strongly supported. Spencer, in fact, went further than most of his ministerial colleagues, including Gladstone himself, in arguing for the setting up of government tribunals to enforce fair rents on Irish landlords.\n\nSpencer, along with the successive [[Chief Secretary for Ireland|Chief Secretaries for Ireland]], [[Chichester Parkinson-Fortescue, 1st Baron Carlingford|Chichester Fortescue]] and Spencer's own cousin, [[Spencer Cavendish, 8th Duke of Devonshire|Lord Hartington]], supported coercive legislation to deal with the increase in agrarian crime, but at the same time supported a policy of releasing [[Fenian]] prisoners when possible. Spencer also had to deal during his tenure with Gladstone's Irish Universities Bill. In spite of Spencer's efforts to secure the support of the Catholic hierarchy for the bill, they opposed it, and it went down to defeat in the commons in March 1873. The government lingered on for a further year, until the election defeat of February 1874, when Spencer found himself out of office. When Gladstone returned to power for his second government in 1880, Spencer joined the Cabinet as [[Lord President of the Council]], having responsibility for education policy, and was partially responsible for several major educational reforms of the period. The increasingly tense situation in Ireland, however, commanded an increasing portion of Spencer's time. In May 1882, Gladstone's decision to release the Irish Nationalist leader [[Charles Stewart Parnell]] from prison led to the resignation of the hardline Chief Secretary for Ireland, [[William Edward Forster|W. E. Forster]]. As a result, Spencer, while retaining his seat in the cabinet and position as Lord President, was again appointed Lord Lieutenant to take charge of the government's Irish policy.\n[[File:MaolraSeoighe.jpeg|thumb|100px|left|Spencer received condemnation from Irish Nationalist sources for his role in the trial for the [[Maamtrasna murders]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url= https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/a-wrongful-hanging-in-connemara-1882-1.2650574\n|title= A wrongful hanging in Connemara, 1882\n|date= 20 May 2016\n|work= The Irish Times\n|page= \n}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Shield of arms of John Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer, KG, PC.png|thumb|262px|right|Shield of arms of John Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer, as displayed on his Order of the Garter stall plate in St. George's Chapel.]]\nSpencer and his new chief secretary, Gladstone's nephew and Hartington's brother [[Lord Frederick Cavendish]], crossed to Ireland on 5 May, but Cavendish and the permanent under-secretary, [[Thomas Henry Burke (civil servant)|Thomas Henry Burke]], were [[Phoenix Park Murders|murdered]] by extremist Irish nationalists the next day in [[Phoenix Park]], Dublin, while walking to the [[\u00c1ras an Uachtar\u00e1in|Viceregal Lodge]] where Spencer was staying. Spencer, assisted by [[Sir George Trevelyan, 2nd Baronet|George Trevelyan]], his new secretary, was now faced with the difficult task of pacifying Ireland. Spencer acted quickly to reform the Irish police forces and destroy the secret societies which had been responsible for the murders. He attracted heavy criticism for his poor handling of a group of murders in [[Maamtrasna]] - one of the supposed criminals, [[Myles Joyce]], had been hanged while still proclaiming his innocence, leading to a great deal of condemnation of Spencer from Irish Nationalist sources. The end of Spencer's second tenure as viceroy saw the successful visit of the [[Edward VII|Prince]] and [[Alexandra of Denmark|Princess of Wales]] to Ireland, but Spencer's efforts to get the [[Queen Victoria|Queen]] to agree to the creation of a royal residence in Ireland were unsuccessful.\n\n==Political career, 1885\u20131905==\nBy 1885, Gladstone's second government was in a very weak position, largely as a result of the death of [[Charles George Gordon|Charles Gordon]], and Spencer's efforts to renew the Irish Crimes Act and secure passage of a land purchase bill ran into opposition from the radicals in the Cabinet - [[Joseph Chamberlain]] and [[Sir Charles Dilke, 2nd Baronet|Sir Charles Dilke]] - who hoped to use the opportunity of the legislation to pass a greater measure of local self-government for Ireland. The issue remained up in the air when Gladstone's government fell in early June. During the interval between the fall of Gladstone's second government and the beginning of his third, in February 1886, Spencer became a convert to [[Irish Home Rule]], unlike most of the other leading Whigs, who deserted to [[Liberal Unionist Party|Liberal Unionism]]. Spencer would serve as Lord President in Gladstone's third government, and was instrumental in the formulation of Gladstone's home rule legislation. After the defeat of the bill, Spencer joined his chief in opposition. Spencer's position on home rule led to his social ostracism by other members of his class, including the Queen herself, and spent much of his period in opposition getting his personal finances in order. He also acted from 1888 as chairman of the [[Northamptonshire County Council]], and continued to work with Gladstone and other liberal leaders in determining the shape of a home rule bill in the next liberal government.\n\n[[File:5 Earl Spencer.jpg|thumb|200px|Lord Spencer, in the robes of a [[Order of the Garter|Knight of the Garter (KG)]].]]\nWhen the Liberals returned to power in August 1892, Spencer was appointed [[List of the First Lords of the Admiralty|First Lord of the Admiralty]]. Gladstone's opposition to Spencer's policy, following the recommendations of the [[Sea Lords]], of naval expansion, led to Gladstone's final resignation in March 1894. Gladstone himself nonetheless hoped that Spencer would be his successor, but the Queen did not seek his advice, and chose [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|Lord Rosebery]] instead. Spencer continued to serve under Rosebery, and went out when the Liberal government fell in June 1895. In his later years, Spencer remained active in politics. Spencer was a key support for the Liberal leader in the Commons, [[Henry Campbell-Bannerman]] (who had previously been Spencer's Chief Secretary at the end of his second vice-regency) during the [[Boer War]], holding to the Liberal leader's middle course between the active anti-war position of the Radicals and the pro-war position of Rosebery's Liberal Imperialists. Following [[John Wodehouse, 1st Earl of Kimberley|Lord Kimberley's]] death in 1902, Spencer was elected Liberal leader in the House of Lords. Despite health problems, he was rumoured as late as February 1905 to be a potential candidate for Liberal prime minister should the Liberals soon return to power, as by then seemed likely as a result of the Unionist split over tariff reform. However, on 11 October of that year he suffered a major stroke which ended his political career, only two months shy of the Liberals' return to power.\n<!--* ''& chancellorship of the [[Victoria University (UK)|Victoria University]]-<nowiki/>{[[Leeds]]; [[Liverpool]]; [[Manchester]]}.''-->\n\n==Rifle Volunteers==\nAn [[Volunteer Force#The British Army following the Crimea|invasion scare in 1859]] led to a War Office decision to call for [[Volunteer Force#Creation of the Volunteer Force|local Volunteer Corps]] to be established.<ref>[Ian F. W. Beckett, ''Riflemen Form: A study of the Rifle Volunteer Movement 1859\u20131908'', Aldershot: Ogilby Trusts, 1982, {{ISBN|0-85936-271-X}}.</ref> The [[War Office]] issued a Circular Letter on 12 May inviting volunteers, and within three days Spencer had offered to raise a company from his tenants at [[Althorp]]. It became the [[1st Northamptonshire Rifle Volunteer Corps|1st (Althorp Rifles) Northamptonshire Rifle Volunteer Corps]] with Spencer appointed to command in the rank of captain on 29 August 1859.<ref>Beckett, pp. 24 & 52.</ref><ref>Gurney, p. 314.</ref><ref>Westlake, pp. 190\u20131.</ref>\n\nThe 1st Northampton RVC sang a song to the tune of [[The British Grenadiers]]:\n::''Now every man of sense, Sir,<br/>Should welcome with three cheers<br/>And rally round Lord Spencer<br/>and the Althorp Volunteers.''<ref>Beckett, p. 265.</ref>\n\nAfter the separate Northamptonshire RVCs were formed into an administrative battalion the following year, Spencer was promoted to major on 2 April 1861.<ref>''Army List''.</ref><ref>Beckett, p. 47.</ref> When the battalion held its annual camp at Althorp in 1864, Spencer's hospitality included providing his own cook to direct the officers' mess.<ref>Beckett, p. 115.</ref>\n\nAlso in 1859, Spencer was a leading member of the committee that established the [[National Rifle Association of the United Kingdom]], and hosted the committee's meetings at [[Spencer House, London]]. The Association's first competitive meetings were held at [[Wimbledon Common]], part of Spencer's manor of Wimbledon.<ref>Beckett, p. 33.</ref> In 1867 he served on a War Office committee to investigate breech-loading rifles.<ref>Beckett, p. 201.</ref>\n\nLord Spencer was appointed to the [[Honorary Colonel|honorary colonelcy]] of the [[Northamptonshire Yeomanry|Northamptonshire Imperial Yeomanry]] (later the Northamptonshire Yeomanry) on 21 May 1902.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27435|page=3326| date=20 May 1902}}</ref>\n\n==Other public appointments==\nIn 1865 Spencer chaired a royal commission on cattle plague, alongside [[Robert Gascoyne-Cecil, 3rd Marquess of Salisbury|Lord Cranborne]], [[Robert Lowe]] and [[Lyon Playfair, 1st Baron Playfair|Lyon Playfair]].\n\nLord Spencer was [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of Manchester's [[Victoria University (United Kingdom)|Victoria University]].\n\nDuring a visit to [[Exeter]] on 12 July 1902, he was presented with the [[Freedom of the Borough]] of Exeter.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Lord Spencer at Exeter |day_of_week=Monday |date=14 July 1902 |page_number=10 |issue=36819| }}</ref>\n\n==Courtier==\nSpencer served, for most of the period from 1859 to 1866, in the [[royal household]], as a groom first to [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]] and then to the [[Edward VII|Prince of Wales]]. In 1876 he hosted [[Empress Elisabeth of Austria]] who had come to Northamptonshire for a hunting party. The empress stayed at [[Easton Neston house|Easton Neston]], which she rented through her sister, ex-queen [[Maria Sophie of Bavaria|Maria]] of the [[Two Sicilies]].\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Charlotte, Countess Spencer (1835-1903) by Louis William Desanges.jpg|thumb|200px|Charlotte, Countess Spencer (1835\u20131903) (Louis William Desanges).]]\nLord Spencer married [[Charlotte Spencer, Countess Spencer|Charlotte Seymour]], daughter of Frederick Charles William Seymour and granddaughter of [[Lord Hugh Seymour]], on 8 July 1858. The marriage was recorded as childless. Lady Spencer died in October 1903, aged 68. Spencer died at [[Althorp]] in August 1910, aged 74, and was succeeded by his half-brother, [[Charles Spencer, 6th Earl Spencer|Charles]].\n\nIn 1864, Spencer, as [[lord of the manor]] of [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]] through his ownership of [[Wimbledon House]], attempted to get a [[private parliamentary bill]]<ref name=Gazette1>{{London Gazette|date=25 November 1864|issue=22915|pages=5834\u20135835}}</ref> to [[enclosure|enclose]] [[Wimbledon Common]] for the creation of a new park with a house and gardens and to sell part for building. In a landmark decision for English [[common land]], and following an enquiry, permission was refused and a board of conservators was established in 1871<ref name=Gazette2>{{London Gazette|date=25 November 1870|issue=23682|pages=5244\u20135245}}</ref><ref name=Gazette3>{{London Gazette|date=18 August 1871|issue=23768|page=3643}}</ref> to take ownership of the common and preserve it in its natural condition.\n\n==Coat of arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Earl.svg|90px|center]] [[File:Spencer Arms.svg|100px]]\n|creation date= 1 November 1765\n|crest = Out of a Ducal Coronet Or a Griffin's Head Azure gorged with a Bar Gemelle Gules between two Wings expanded of the second\n|coronet = A [[Coronet|Coronet of an Earl]]\n|escutcheon = Quarterly Argent and Gules in the 2nd and 3rd quarters a Fret Or over all on a Bend Sable three Escallops of the first\n|supporters = Dexter:  A Griffin per fess Ermine and Erminois gorged with a Collar Sable the edges flory-counterflory and chained of the last and on the Collar three Escallops Argent;  Sinister:  A Wyvern Erect on his tail Ermine similarly collared and chained\n|motto = Dieu Defend Le Droit (God defend the right)\n}}\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''John Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer'''\n|2= 2. [[Frederick Spencer, 4th Earl Spencer]]\n|3= 3. Georgiana Poyntz\n|4= 4. [[George Spencer, 2nd Earl Spencer]]\n|5= 5. [[Lavinia Spencer, Countess Spencer|Lady Lavinia Bingham]]\n|6= 6. [[William Stephen Poyntz]]\n|7= 7. Hon. Elizabeth Mary Browne\n|8= 8. [[John Spencer, 1st Earl Spencer]]\n|9= 9. [[Georgiana Spencer, Countess Spencer|Georgiana Poyntz]]\n|10= 10. [[Charles Bingham, 1st Earl of Lucan]]\n|11= 11. [[Margaret Bingham|Margaret Smith]]\n|12= 12. William Poyntz\n|13= 13. Isabella Courtenay\n|14= 14. Anthony Browne, 7th [[Viscount Montagu]]\n|15= 15. Frances Mackworth\n|16= 16. Hon. [[John Spencer (British politician)|John Spencer]]\n|17= 17. Lady Georgina Carolina Carteret\n|18= 18. [[Stephen Poyntz]] (= 24)\n|19= 19. Anna Maria Mordaunt (= 25)\n|20= 20. [[Sir John Bingham, 5th Baronet]]\n|21= 21. Anne Vesey\n|22= 22. Sir James Smith\n|23= 23. Grace Dyke\n|24= 24. [[Stephen Poyntz]] (= 18)\n|25= 25. Anna Maria Mordaunt (= 19)\n|26= 26. Kelland Courtenay\n|27= 27. Hon. Elizabeth Montagu\n|28= 28. Anthony Browne, 6th [[Viscount Montagu]]\n|29= 29. Barbara Webb\n|30= 30. [[Herbert Mackworth]]\n|31= 31. Hon. Juliana Digby\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Ian F.W. Beckett, ''Riflemen Form: A study of the Rifle Volunteer Movement 1859\u20131908'', Aldershot: Ogilby Trusts, 1982, {{ISBN|0 85936 271 X}}.\n* Gordon, Peter, \"Spencer, John Poyntz, fifth Earl Spencer (1835-1910),\" ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', 2004-2007.\n* Lt-Col Russell Gurney, ''History of the Northamptonshire Regiment 1742\u20131934'', Aldershot: Gale & Polden, 1935.\n* Ray Westlake, ''Tracing the Rifle Volunteers'', Barnsley: Pen and Sword, 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-84884-211-3}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|John Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer}}\n*{{Hansard-contribs | viscount-althorp | John Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[South Northamptonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Northamptonshire]]\n  | with   =[[Rainald Knightley, 1st Baron Knightley|Rainald Knightley]]\n  | years  = March 1857 \u2013 December 1857\n  | before = [[Richard Henry Howard Vyse|Richard Vyse]]<br />[[Rainald Knightley, 1st Baron Knightley|Rainald Knightley]]\n  | after  = [[Henry Cartwright]]<br />[[Rainald Knightley, 1st Baron Knightley|Rainald Knightley]]\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before=[[James Hamilton, 1st Duke of Abercorn|The Duke of Abercorn]] | title=[[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]] | years=1868\u20131874 | after=[[James Hamilton, 1st Duke of Abercorn|The Duke of Abercorn]]}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Charles Gordon-Lennox, 6th Duke of Richmond|The Duke of Richmond]] | title=[[Lord President of the Council]] | years=1880\u20131883 | after=[[Chichester Parkinson-Fortescue, 1st Baron Carlingford|The Lord Carlingford]]}}\n{{succes