{"title_page": "Samuel Warren (British lawyer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Other people|Samuel Warren}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Samuel Warren\n| image              = Samuel Warren by John Linnell.jpg\n| alt                = Samuel Warren (c. 1835-40), by [[John Linnell (painter)|John Linnell]].\n| caption            = Samuel Warren (c. 1835-40), by [[John Linnell (painter)|John Linnell]].\n| other_names        = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Edinburgh]]\n| occupation         = British writer, lawyer and politician\n| birth_place        = Rackery Farm near Wrexham, [[Denbighshire]], UK\n| death_place        = London, UK\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|df=y|1808|05|23}}\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|1877|07|29|1808|05|23}}\n}}\n'''Samuel Warren''' (23 May 1807 \u2013 29 July 1877), was a British barrister, novelist and MP.\n\n==Life==\nHe was born in Wales at Rackery Farm near Wrexham, [[Denbighshire]], the son of Anne (n\u00e9e Williams) and Rev Dr Samuel Warren, a [[Nonconformist (Protestantism)|Nonconformist]] minister. After studying at the [[Kingswood School]], Bath he attended the [[University of Edinburgh]] to study medicine but then took up law. He became a barrister, wrote several legal text-books, and in 1852 was made Recorder of [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]].\n\nWarren sat in the House of Commons for [[Midhurst (UK Parliament constituency)|Midhurst]] 1856\u20131859, and was a Master in Lunacy 1859\u201377. He was the author of ''[[Passages from the Diary of a late Physician]]'', which appeared (1832\u201337) first in ''[[Blackwood's Magazine]]'', as did also the novel ''[[Ten Thousand a-Year]]'' (1839). Both attracted considerable attention, and were often reprinted and translated. The novel was based on the Alexander Humphrys-Alexander [[Earl of Stirling|Stirling forgery]] case, where a claim was made to a vacant earldom using fake documents. The shallow, profligate young protagonist, Tittlebat Titmouse, is said to be based on [[Edward Oxford]], who tried to assassinate Queen Victoria.\n\nHis last novel, ''Now and Then'' (1847), was a [[social novel]] of criminality and the law, arguing from a [[Methodist]] perspective the moral case for reform. It is realistically observed, based in outline on an actual case in [[Wolverhampton]], but had little success. Some critics thought Warren entertained exaggerated ideas as to the importance of his place in literature. However, his best known work, ''Ten Thousand a Year'', contains social satire rivalling that of [[Thackeray]], written from a Tory standpoint.\n\nHe was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] in April 1835.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.royalsociety.org/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Persons&dsqPos=5&dsqSearch=%28Surname%3D%27warren%27%29 |title=Library and Archiv catalogue |publisher=Royal Society |accessdate=30 October 2010 }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He died in London.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{A Short Biographical Dictionary of English Literature}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-samuel-warren | Samuel Warren }}\n* [https://www.jstor.org/stable/743371  Samuel Warren: A Victorian Law and Literature Practitioner, by C.R.B. Dunlop]\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Warren,+Samuel+(1807-1877) | name=Samuel Warren}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Samuel Warren |birth=1807 |death=1877 |sopt=t }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Midhurst (UK Parliament constituency)|Midhurst]] | before=[[Spencer Horatio Walpole]] | after=[[Sir John Hardy, 1st Baronet|John Hardy]] | years=1856\u20131859}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Warren, Samuel}}\n[[Category:1807 births]]\n[[Category:1877 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Wrexham]]\n[[Category:19th-century British writers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1852\u20131857]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1857\u20131859]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Victorian novelists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Other people|Samuel Warren}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Samuel Warren\n| image              = Samuel Warren by John Linnell.jpg\n| alt                = Samuel Warren (c. 1835-40), by [[John Linnell (painter)|John Linnell]].\n| caption            = Samuel Warren (c. 1835-40), by [[John Linnell (painter)|John Linnell]].\n| other_names        = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Edinburgh]]\n| occupation         = British writer, lawyer and politician\n| birth_place        = Rackery Farm near Wrexham, [[Denbighshire]], UK\n| death_place        = London, UK\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|df=y|1808|05|23}}\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|1877|07|29|1808|05|23}}\n}}\n'''Samuel Warren''' (23 May 1807 \u2013 29 July 1877), was a British barrister, novelist and MP.\n\n==Life==\nHe was born in Wales at Rackery Farm near Wrexham, [[Denbighshire]], the son of Anne (n\u00e9e Williams) and Rev Dr Samuel Warren, a [[Nonconformist (Protestantism)|Nonconformist]] minister. After studying at the [[Kingswood School]], Bath he attended the [[University of Edinburgh]] to study medicine but then took up law. He became a barrister, wrote several legal text-books, and in 1852 was made Recorder of [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]].\n\nWarren sat in the House of Commons for [[Midhurst (UK Parliament constituency)|Midhurst]] 1856\u20131859, and was a Master in Lunacy 1859-77. He was the author of ''[[Passages from the Diary of a late Physician]]'', which appeared (1832\u201337) first in ''[[Blackwood's Magazine]]'', as did also the novel ''[[Ten Thousand a-Year]]'' (1839). Both attracted considerable attention, and were often reprinted and translated. The novel was based on the Alexander Humphrys-Alexander [[Earl of Stirling|Stirling forgery]] case, where a claim was made to a vacant earldom using fake documents. The shallow, profligate young protagonist, Tittlebat Titmouse, is said to be based on [[Edward Oxford]], who tried to assassinate Queen Victoria.\n\nHis last novel, ''Now and Then'' (1847), was a [[social novel]] of criminality and the law, arguing from a [[Methodist]] perspective the moral case for reform. It is realistically observed, based in outline on an actual case in [[Wolverhampton]], but had little success. Some critics thought Warren entertained exaggerated ideas as to the importance of his place in literature. However, his best known work, ''Ten Thousand a Year'', contains social satire rivalling that of [[Thackeray]], written from a Tory standpoint.\n\nHe was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] in April 1835.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.royalsociety.org/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Persons&dsqPos=5&dsqSearch=%28Surname%3D%27warren%27%29 |title=Library and Archiv catalogue |publisher=Royal Society |accessdate=30 October 2010 }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He died in London.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{A Short Biographical Dictionary of English Literature}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-samuel-warren | Samuel Warren }}\n* [https://www.jstor.org/stable/743371  Samuel Warren: A Victorian Law and Literature Practitioner, by C.R.B. Dunlop]\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Warren,+Samuel+(1807-1877) | name=Samuel Warren}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Samuel Warren |birth=1807 |death=1877 |sopt=t }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Midhurst (UK Parliament constituency)|Midhurst]] | before=[[Spencer Horatio Walpole]] | a