{"title_page": "Opel GT", "text_new": "{{short description|Sports car manufactured by Opel}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n|name = Opel GT\n|image = Opel_GT,_Bj._1973_am_16.07.2006.jpg\n|manufacturer = [[General Motors]]\n|production = 1968\u20131973<br/>2007\u20132009\n|successor = [[Opel Manta]] (indirect)\n}}\n\nThe '''Opel GT''' is a front-engine, rear-drive two-seat [[sports car]] manufactured and marketed by [[Opel]] in two generations &mdash; separated by a 34-year hiatus.\n\nThe first generation Opel GT (1968<ref>''The Guardian'' page 6 Friday OPEL ANNOUNCES NEW SPORTS CAR 27 September 1968 \"Opel announces it is going into production with a two door two-seater the Opel GT.\"</ref> -1973) debuted as a styling exercise in 1965 at the [[Paris Motor Show|Paris]] and [[Frankfurt Motor Show|Frankfurt]] motor shows.<ref name=Autocar1968>{{cite journal| title = Opel GT Corvette for Europe?| journal = [[Autocar (magazine)|Autocar]] | volume =  129 |number= 3790 | page = 55 |date = 3 October 1968}}</ref> The production vehicle used mechanical components from the contemporary [[Opel Kadett|Opel Kadett B]] and two-door hard top bodywork by [[France|French]] contractor [[Brissonneau & Lotz]]. The styling of the GT was often cited as similar to the [[Chevrolet Corvette (C3)|1968 Chevrolet Corvette]] which went on sale in September 1967.<ref>[http://auto.howstuffworks.com/opel-gt.htm Opel GT] at Howstuffworks.com</ref>\n\nOpel marketed a second generation ''GT'' (2007-2009) as a [[badge engineering|rebadged]] variant of the [[Saturn Sky]]/[[Pontiac Solstice]] two-seater convertible, manufactured in [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]], [[Delaware]], [[United States|USA]].\n\nIn 2016, Opel introduced the ''GT Concept'' at the 2016 [[Geneva Motor Show]] as a lightweight, turbocharged, rear-wheel drive two-seater.<ref name=\"concept\">{{cite web\n  | title = Opel GT Concept: The German Mini-Corvette Returns\n  | publisher = Car & Driver\n  | author =  ALEXANDER STOKLOSA\n  | date = January 2016\n  | url = http://www.caranddriver.com/news/opel-gt-concept-official-photos-and-info-news}}</ref>\n\n==GT (1968\u20131973)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name= GT\n| image= Opel GT 17RM0442.jpg\n| production= 1968-1973\n| transmission=4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]<br>3-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]\n| assembly=West Germany: [[Bochum]]\n| engine={{unbulleted list | {{convert|1078|cc|cuin|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Opel OHV engine#1.1|OHV]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] (gasoline)|{{convert|1897|cc|cuin|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Opel cam-in-head engine#1.9 liter I4|CIH]]'' I4 (gasoline)}}\n| class= [[sports car]]\n| body_style=2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout=[[Mid-engine design#FMR layout \u2013 Front Mid-engine / Rear-wheel drive|front mid-engined, rear-wheel drive]]\n| wheelbase= {{convert|2415|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length={{convert|4113|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width={{convert|1580|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height={{convert|1225|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight={{convert|845|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\u2013{{convert|940|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n}}\n[[File:Opel GTJ ca 1972 Schaffen-Diest.jpg|left|thumb|The reduced specification GT/J (for \"Junior\") introduced in 1971 represented an attempt to broaden the appeal of the Opel GT.]]\n[[File:Opel GT red h.jpg|left|thumb|Rear view]]\n[[File:1969 Opel GT A-L 1900 Interior.jpg|thumb|left|GT interior]]\n[[File:A visitors Opel GT A-L, 1971 (7126133427) (cropped).jpg|thumb|283px|Opel GT with headlights turned up]]\n[[File:Opel 50 Jahre Design (14520095774).jpg|thumb|left|When turning, both headlights turn in the same direction]]\nThe Opel GT was equipped with a base 1.1&nbsp;L [[Overhead valve|OHV]] [[Inline-four engine|inline-four]] engine, which produced 67&nbsp;hp (SAE) at 6,000&nbsp;rpm. However, most buyers chose an optional 1.9&nbsp;L [[Opel cam-in-head engine|camshaft in head]] engine, which produced 102&nbsp;hp (SAE) at 5200 to 5400&nbsp;rpm. Some of the early 1968 models also came with a slightly higher compression \"H\" code cylinder head. In 1971, due to emissions regulations, Opel reduced the [[compression ratio]] of the 1.9&nbsp;L engine used in the US and output fell to 83&nbsp;hp (SAE). There was also a GT/J model, which was a less expensive version of the 1900-engined GT which was sold only in Europe. Standard transmission was a manual four-speed. A three-speed automatic was available with the 1.9&nbsp;L engine. The model run of the Opel GT was from 1968 to 1973.\n\nThe Opel GT uses a steel unibody and a [[Mid-engine design#FMR layout \u2013 Front Mid-engine / Rear-wheel drive|front mid-engined, rear-wheel drive]] layout. The engine is mounted far back in the chassis to improve weight distribution. Front [[suspension (vehicle)|suspension]] consists of upper [[Control arm|A-arms]] and a lower transverse leaf spring \u2014 aside from the Opel's styling, the unusual use of a transverse leaf-spring in the suspension was another remarkable commonality with Chevrolet's Corvette. A live axle and coil springs are used in the rear. The power-assisted braking system uses discs in the front, drums in the rear. Steering is unassisted.\n\nOne unusual feature of the Opel GT is the operation of the [[Hidden headlamps|pop-up up and down headlights]]. They are manually operated, by way of a large lever along the center console next to the shifter. Unlike most pop-up headlights, they both rotate in the same direction (counterclockwise from inside the car) about a longitudinal axis.\n\nDesigned by Opel stylist Erhard Schnell,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://opelpost.com/06/2014/opel-design-studio-first-of-its-kind-in-europe/ |title= Opel GT designend by Stylist Erhard Schnell}}</ref> the GT is a [[fastback]], that has neither an externally accessible trunk nor a conventional [[hatchback]]. There is a parcel shelf behind the seats that can only be accessed through the main doors. Behind the parcel shelf is a fold-up panel that conceals a spare tire and jack.\n\nDuring 1968 to 1973, a total of 103,463 cars were sold. The most [[collectible]] GTs are probably the first few hundred cars hand-assembled in 1968 and the 1968\u20131970 models with the 1.1&nbsp;L engine, which totaled 3,573 cars. Of the later cars, 10,760 were the cheaper model (GT/J), which lacked nearly all chrome parts and offered fewer standard features. In some markets, items like a [[limited slip differential]], front and rear anti-sway bars, heated rear window, and engine bay light were standard, although most cars were shipped without them.\n\nIn North America, the GT was sold at Buick dealerships. Reasons for ending production were the need to redesign the car to remain competitive with up-and-coming sports models, such as the Datsun 240Z, as well as the termination of [[Brissonneau and Lotz]]' bodybuilding contract.  Unusually for the period, there was no [[Vauxhall Motors|Vauxhall]] equivalent model to the GT sold in the United Kingdom.\n\nThe Opel GT was also used by Italian coachbuilder [[Sergio Coggiola]] to create the '''Opel Sylvia GT''', an angular design of the folded-paper school. The 1973 Sylvia was also designed with an eye to safety.<ref name=WC75>{{Cite book | title = World Cars 1975 | publisher = L'Editrice dell'Automobile LEA/Herald Books | location = Pelham, NY | ref = WC75 | page = 19 | year = 1975 | isbn = 0-910714-07-X }}</ref>\n\nAutomotive magazine ''[[Road & Track]]'' reviewed the GT in their June 1969 issue, recording 0\u201396&nbsp;km/h in 10.8 seconds and a top speed of 182&nbsp;km/h. ''Road & Track'' also found the car to have strong understeer, suggesting the 165x13 tires to be too small, although the ride was comfortable.{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==GT (roadster) (2007\u20132010)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n|name         = GT (roadster)\n|image        = Opel GT front.JPG\n|aka          = [[Saturn Sky]] (USA & Canada)<br>GM Daewoo G2X (South Korea)\n|production   = 2007\u20132009\n|model_years  = 2007\u20132010\n|assembly     = {{ubl |United States: [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]], [[Delaware]] ([[Wilmington Assembly]])}}\n|engine       = 1998&nbsp;cc [[Inline-four engine|I4]]\n|successor    =\n|predecessor  = [[Opel Speedster]]\n|platform     = [[GM Kappa platform|Kappa platform]]\n|class        = [[Sports car]] ([[S-segment|S]])\n|body_style   = 2-door [[Roadster (automobile)|roadster]]\n|layout       = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|FR layout]]\n|related      = [[Pontiac Solstice]]\n|wheelbase    = {{convert|2415|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|length       = {{convert|4091|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|width        = {{convert|1813|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|height       = {{convert|1276|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|weight       = {{convert|1325|-|1406|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n|designer     = [[Franz von Holzhausen]]\n}}\n\n{{Main article|Saturn Sky}}\n\nThe new Opel GT was produced from 2007 to 2010. It was a [[badge engineering|badge engineered]] variant of the [[Pontiac Solstice]] and the [[Saturn Sky]] and was available solely with the 2.0&nbsp;L, {{convert|260|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} [[fuel injection#Direct injection|direct injection]] [[Turbocharger|turbocharged]] [[GM Ecotec engine#SIDI|Ecotec]] four-cylinder engine. It had 18-inch [[alloy wheel]]s. The car replaced the [[Opel Speedster]] in the European lineup; however, it is not sold in right-hand drive in the UK, thus there is no replacement for the Vauxhall VX220. The situation is similar to Holden in Australia, as the [[Saturn Sky]] and [[Pontiac Solstice]] are produced at a North American plant, which does not have the necessary tooling for producing right-hand drive vehicles. \n\n===Production by model year===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Model Year\n! Total Opel GT (Roadster) Production<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gm.com/corporate/investor_information/sales_prod/hist_prod.jsp |title=General Motors: Investors: Sales and Production Reports: Historical Production |publisher=GM |date=2009-07-10 |accessdate=2009-11-01}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2007\n| 2,365\n|-\n| 2008\n| 4,851\n|-\n| 2009\n| 301\n|-\n| 2010\n| 2\n|-\n|''' Total'''\n| '''7,519'''\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n==2016 concepts==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name         = 2016 concept\n| image        = 2016-03-01 Geneva Motor Show G215.JPG\n| aka          = \n| production   = \n| model_years  = \n| engine       = 1.0&nbsp;L ''[[GM Family 0 engine#Generation III|LDB]]'' [[Straight-three engine|I3]] ([[turbocharger|turbo]] [[gasoline engine|gasoline]])\n| platform     = \n| body_style   = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| transmission = 6-speed [[Semi-automatic transmission|semi-automatic]]\n| layout       = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout#Front mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|FMR layout]]\n| related      = \n| wheelbase    = \n| length       = \n| width        = \n| height       = \n| weight       = {{convert|2200|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n| designer     = \n}}\n\nThe 2016 Opel GT concept debuted on 27 January 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1102072_rear-wheel-drive-opel-gt-sports-car-concept-revealed|title=Rear-Wheel-Drive Opel GT Sports Car Concept Revealed|author=Vijayenthiran, Viknesh|work=Motor Authority|date=2016-01-27|accessdate=2016-01-27}}</ref> Built on an all-new compact rear-wheel-drive platform, the GT has a lightweight construction and stripped down interior. Power comes from a turbocharged 1.0-liter three-cylinder engine producing 145&nbsp;hp with a 6-speed semi-automatic gearbox.\n\nThe concept features historic design cues associated with Opel's past products; the twin tailpipes with the GT wordmark in the middle are reminiscent of those on the original 1965 GT prototype.\n\nThe car made its first public debut on 1 March at the [[Geneva Motor Show#2016|2016 Geneva Motor Show]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2016/01/20/opel-gt-concept-geneva-teaser-video/|title=GM has a new Opel GT concept in store for Geneva|author=Joseph, Noah|work=Autoblog|date=2016-01-20|accessdate=2016-01-27}}</ref> A production version has been conjectured to follow in 2018, commemorating the 50th anniversary of the original Opel GT's unveiling in 1968,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/the-opel-gt-its-coming-back/|title=The Opel GT\u2014It\u2019s Coming Back [UPDATE]|author=Meiners, Jens|work=[[Car and Driver]]|date=2016-01-21|accessdate=2016-01-27}}</ref> and Opel hasn't ruled out the possibility.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carscoops.com/2016/03/opel-gt-concept-might-gain-production.html|title=Opel GT Concept Might Gain Production Version, Use Mokka's AWD System|author=Gnaticov, Cristian|work=Carscoops|date=2016-03-22|accessdate=2016-06-14}}</ref>\n\nUnfortunately, The Opel GT concept has been cancelled due to shrinking market for sports cars and also due to Opel's acquisition by [[Groupe PSA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gmauthority.com/blog/2016/02/opel-gt-concept-has-little-production-intent/|title=Opel GT Concept Has Little Production Intent|author=Szymkowski, Sean|work=GM Authority|date=2016-02-01|accessdate=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n[[File:AutoCl\u00e1ssico 2016 OpelGT DSCN4407 copy (32140989732) (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|280px|At the October 2016 Portugal AutoCl\u00e1ssico show, a racing version with full roll-cage and widened sports body was also shown]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite book | year = 1997 | title = Opel GT Projekt 1484 | author = Henrion/M\u00fcller | publisher = Podszun | isbn = 3-86133-170-5 }}\n*{{cite book | year = n.d. | title = Opel GT Gold Portfolio 1968\u20131973 | author = road test article compilation | publisher = Brooklands Books | isbn = 1-85520-326-X}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Opel GT}}\n* [http://www.opelclub.com/ Opel Motorsport Club]\n* [http://www.opelgt.com/ The Classic Opel Community]\n* [http://www.visualopel.com/ VisualOpel - Illustrations, diagrams, and parts]\n* [http://www.kappaperformance.com/forum/ Forum for the 2007-2009 Opel GT]\n* [http://www.opelgtsource.com/ Opel GT Source]\n\n{{Opel}}\n{{Classic Opel timeline}}\n{{Opel timeline}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Opel Gt}}\n[[Category:Opel vehicles|GT]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:Roadsters]]\n[[Category:1970s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1968]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2006]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sports car manufactured by Opel}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n|name = Opel GT\n|image = Opel_GT,_Bj._1973_am_16.07.2006.jpg\n|manufacturer = [[General Motors]]\n|production = 1968\u20131973<br/>2007\u20132009\n|successor = [[Opel Manta]] (indirect)\n}}\n\nThe '''Opel GT''' is a front-engine, rear-drive two-seat [[sports car]] manufactured and marketed by [[Opel]] in two generations &mdash; separated by a 34-year hiatus.\n\nThe first generation Opel GT (1968<ref>''The Guardian'' page 6 Friday OPEL ANNOUNCES NEW SPORTS CAR 27 September 1968 \"Opel announces it is going into production with a two door two-seater the Opel GT.\"</ref> -1973) debuted as a styling exercise in 1965 at the [[Paris Motor Show|Paris]] and [[Frankfurt Motor Show|Frankfurt]] motor shows.<ref name=Autocar1968>{{cite journal| title = Opel GT Corvette for Europe?| journal = [[Autocar (magazine)|Autocar]] | volume =  129 |number= 3790 | page = 55 |date = 3 October 1968}}</ref> The production vehicle used mechanical components from the contemporary [[Opel Kadett|Opel Kadett B]] and two-door hard top bodywork by [[France|French]] contractor [[Brissonneau & Lotz]]. The styling of the GT was often cited as similar to the [[Chevrolet Corvette (C3)|1968 Chevrolet Corvette]] which went on sale in September 1967.<ref>[http://auto.howstuffworks.com/opel-gt.htm Opel GT] at Howstuffworks.com</ref>\n\nOpel marketed a second generation ''GT'' (2007-2009) as a [[badge engineering|rebadged]] variant of the [[Saturn Sky]]/[[Pontiac Solstice]] two-seater convertible, manufactured in [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]], [[Delaware]], [[United States|USA]].\n\nIn 2016, Opel introduced the ''GT Concept'' at the 2016 [[Geneva Motor Show]] as a lightweight, turbocharged, rear-wheel drive two-seater.<ref name=\"concept\">{{cite web\n  | title = Opel GT Concept: The German Mini-Corvette Returns\n  | publisher = Car & Driver\n  | author =  ALEXANDER STOKLOSA\n  | date = January 2016\n  | url = http://www.caranddriver.com/news/opel-gt-concept-official-photos-and-info-news}}</ref>\n\n==GT (1968\u20131973)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name= GT\n| image= Opel GT 17RM0442.jpg\n| production= 1968-1973\n| transmission=4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]<br>3-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]\n| assembly=West Germany: [[Bochum]]\n| engine={{unbulleted list | {{convert|1078|cc|cuin|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Opel OHV engine#1.1|OHV]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] (gasoline)|{{convert|1897|cc|cuin|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Opel cam-in-head engine#1.9 liter I4|CIH]]'' I4 (gasoline)}}\n| class= [[sports car]]\n| body_style=2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout=[[Mid-engine design#FMR layout \u2013 Front Mid-engine / Rear-wheel drive|front mid-engined, rear-wheel drive]]\n| wheelbase= {{convert|2415|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length={{convert|4113|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width={{convert|1580|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height={{convert|1225|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight={{convert|845|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\u2013{{convert|940|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n}}\n[[File:Opel GTJ ca 1972 Schaffen-Diest.jpg|left|thumb|The reduced specification GT/J (for \"Junior\") introduced in 1971 represented an attempt to broaden the appeal of the Opel GT.]]\n[[File:Opel GT red h.jpg|left|thumb|Rear view]]\n[[File:1969 Opel GT A-L 1900 Interior.jpg|thumb|left|GT interior]]\n[[File:A visitors Opel GT A-L, 1971 (7126133427) (cropped).jpg|thumb|283px|Opel GT with headlights turned up]]\n[[File:Opel 50 Jahre Design (14520095774).jpg|thumb|left|When turning, both headlights turn in the same direction]]\nThe Opel GT was equipped with a base 1.1&nbsp;L [[Overhead valve|OHV]] [[Inline-four engine|inline-four]] engine, which produced 67&nbsp;hp (SAE) at 6,000&nbsp;rpm. However, most buyers chose an optional 1.9&nbsp;L [[Opel cam-in-head engine|camshaft in head]] engine, which produced 102&nbsp;hp (SAE) at 5200 to 5400&nbsp;rpm. Some of the early 1968 models also came with a slightly higher compression \"H\" code cylinder head. In 1971, due to emissions regulations, Opel reduced the [[compression ratio]] of the 1.9&nbsp;L engine used in the US and output fell to 83&nbsp;hp (SAE). There was also a GT/J model, which was a less expensive version of the 1900-engined GT which was sold only in Europe. Standard transmission was a manual four-speed. A three-speed automatic was available with the 1.9&nbsp;L engine. The model run of the Opel GT was from 1968 to 1973.\n\nThe Opel GT uses a steel unibody and a [[Mid-engine design#FMR layout \u2013 Front Mid-engine / Rear-wheel drive|front mid-engined, rear-wheel drive]] layout. The engine is mounted far back in the chassis to improve weight distribution. Front [[suspension (vehicle)|suspension]] consists of upper [[Control arm|A-arms]] and a lower transverse leaf spring \u2014 aside from the Opel's styling, the unusual use of a transverse leaf-spring in the suspension was another remarkable commonality with Chevrolet's Corvette. A live axle and coil springs are used in the rear. The power-assisted braking system uses discs in the front, drums in the rear. Steering is unassisted.\n\nOne unusual feature of the Opel GT is the operation of the [[Hidden headlamps|pop-up up and down headlights]]. They are manually operated, by way of a large lever along the center console next to the shifter. Unlike most pop-up headlights, they both rotate in the same direction (counterclockwise from inside the car) about a longitudinal axis.\n\nDesigned by Opel stylist Erhard Schnell,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://opelpost.com/06/2014/opel-design-studio-first-of-its-kind-in-europe/ |title= Opel GT designend by Stylist Erhard Schnell}}</ref> the GT is a [[fastback]], that has neither an externally accessible trunk nor a conventional [[hatchback]]. There is a parcel shelf behind the seats that can only be accessed through the main doors. Behind the parcel shelf is a fold-up panel that conceals a spare tire and jack.\n\nDuring 1968 to 1973, a total of 103,463 cars were sold. The most [[collectible]] GTs are probably the first few hundred cars hand-assembled in 1968 and the 1968\u20131970 models with the 1.1&nbsp;L engine, which totaled 3,573 cars. Of the later cars, 10,760 were the cheaper model (GT/J), which lacked nearly all chrome parts and offered fewer standard features. In some markets, items like a [[limited slip differential]], front and rear anti-sway bars, heated rear window, and engine bay light were standard, although most cars were shipped without them.\n\nIn North America, the GT was sold at Buick dealerships. Reasons for ending production were the need to redesign the car to remain competitive with up-and-coming sports models, such as the Datsun 240Z, as well as the termination of [[Brissonneau and Lotz]]' bodybuilding contract.  Unusually for the period, there was no [[Vauxhall Motors|Vauxhall]] equivalent model to the GT sold in the United Kingdom.\n\nThe Opel GT was also used by Italian coachbuilder [[Sergio Coggiola]] to create the '''Opel Sylvia GT''', an angular design of the folded-paper school. The 1973 Sylvia was also designed with an eye to safety.<ref name=WC75>{{Cite book | title = World Cars 1975 | publisher = L'Editrice dell'Automobile LEA/Herald Books | location = Pelham, NY | ref = WC75 | page = 19 | year = 1975 | isbn = 0-910714-07-X }}</ref>\n\nAutomotive magazine ''[[Road & Track]]'' reviewed the GT in their June 1969 issue, recording 0\u201396&nbsp;km/h in 10.8 seconds and a top speed of 182&nbsp;km/h. ''Road & Track'' also found the car to have strong understeer, suggesting the 165x13 tires to be too small, although the ride was comfortable.{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==GT (roadster) (2007\u20132010)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n|name         = GT (roadster)\n|image        = Opel GT front.JPG\n|aka          = [[Saturn Sky]] (USA & Canada)<br>GM Daewoo G2X (South Korea)\n|production   = 2007\u20132009\n|model_years  = 2007\u20132010\n|assembly     = {{ubl |United States: [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]], [[Delaware]] ([[Wilmington Assembly]])}}\n|engine       = 1998&nbsp;cc [[Inline-four engine|I4]]\n|successor    =\n|predecessor  = [[Opel Speedster]]\n|platform     = [[GM Kappa platform|Kappa platform]]\n|class        = [[Sports car]] ([[S-segment|S]])\n|body_style   = 2-door [[Roadster (automobile)|roadster]]\n|layout       = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|FR layout]]\n|related      = [[Pontiac Solstice]]\n|wheelbase    = {{convert|2415|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|length       = {{convert|4091|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|width        = {{convert|1813|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|height       = {{convert|1276|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|weight       = {{convert|1325|-|1406|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n|designer     = [[Franz von Holzhausen]]\n}}\n\n{{Main article|Saturn Sky}}\n\nThe new Opel GT was produced from 2007 to 2010. It was a [[badge engineering|badge engineered]] variant of the [[Pontiac Solstice]] and the [[Saturn Sky]] and was available solely with the 2.0&nbsp;L, {{convert|260|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} [[fuel injection#Direct injection|direct injection]] [[Turbocharger|turbocharged]] [[GM Ecotec engine#SIDI|Ecotec]] four-cylinder engine. It had 18-inch [[alloy wheel]]s. The car replaced the [[Opel Speedster]] in the European lineup; however, it is not sold in right-hand drive in the UK, thus there is no replacement for the Vauxhall VX220. The situation is similar to Holden in Australia, as the [[Saturn Sky]] and [[Pontiac Solstice]] are produced at a North American plant, which does not have the necessary tooling for producing right-hand drive vehicles. \n\n===Production by model year===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Model Year\n! Total Opel GT (Roadster) Production<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gm.com/corporate/investor_information/sales_prod/hist_prod.jsp |title=General Motors: Investors: Sales and Production Reports: Historical Production |publisher=GM |date=2009-07-10 |accessdate=2009-11-01}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2007\n| 2,365\n|-\n| 2008\n| 4,851\n|-\n| 2009\n| 301\n|-\n| 2010\n| 2\n|-\n|''' Total'''\n| '''7,519'''\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n==2016 concepts==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name         = 2016 concept\n| image        = 2016-03-01 Geneva Motor Show G215.JPG\n| aka          = \n| production   = \n| model_years  = \n| engine       = 1.0&nbsp;L ''[[GM Family 0 engine#Generation III|LDB]]'' [[Straight-three engine|I3]] ([[turbocharger|turbo]] [[gasoline engine|gasoline]])\n| platform     = \n| body_style   = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| transmission = 6-speed [[Semi-automatic transmission|semi-automatic]]\n| layout       = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout#Front mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|FMR layout]]\n| related      = \n| wheelbase    = \n| length       = \n| width        = \n| height       = \n| weight       = {{convert|2200|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n| designer     = \n}}\n\nThe 2016 Opel GT concept debuted on 27 January 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1102072_rear-wheel-drive-opel-gt-sports-car-concept-revealed|title=Rear-Wheel-Drive Opel GT Sports Car Concept Revealed|author=Vijayenthiran, Viknesh|work=Motor Authority|date=2016-01-27|accessdate=2016-01-27}}</ref> Built on an all-new compact rear-wheel-drive platform, the GT has a lightweight construction and stripped down interior. Power comes from a turbocharged 1.0-liter three-cylinder engine producing 145&nbsp;hp with a 6-speed semi-automatic gearbox.\n\nThe concept features historic design cues associated with Opel's past products; the twin tailpipes with the GT wordmark in the middle are reminiscent of those on the original 1965 GT prototype.\n\nThe car made its first public debut on 1 March at the [[Geneva Motor Show#2016|2016 Geneva Motor Show]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2016/01/20/opel-gt-concept-geneva-teaser-video/|title=GM has a new Opel GT concept in store for Geneva|author=Joseph, Noah|work=Autoblog|date=2016-01-20|accessdate=2016-01-27}}</ref> A production version has been conjectured to follow in 2018, commemorating the 50th anniversary of the original Opel GT's unveiling in 1968,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/the-opel-gt-its-coming-back/|title=The Opel GT\u2014It\u2019s Coming Back [UPDATE]|author=Meiners, Jens|work=[[Car and Driver]]|date=2016-01-21|accessdate=2016-01-27}}</ref> and Opel hasn't ruled out the possibility.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carscoops.com/2016/03/opel-gt-concept-might-gain-production.html|title=Opel GT Concept Might Gain Production Version, Use Mokka's AWD System|author=Gnaticov, Cristian|work=Carscoops|date=2016-03-22|accessdate=2016-06-14}}</ref>\n\nUnfortunately, The Opel GT concept has been cancelled due to shrinking market for sports cars and also due to Opel's acquisition by [[Groupe PSA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gmauthority.com/blog/2016/02/opel-gt-concept-has-little-production-intent/|title=Opel GT Concept Has Little Production Intent|author=Szymkowski, Sean|work=GM Authority|date=2016-02-01|accessdate=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n[[File:AutoCl\u00e1ssico 2016 OpelGT DSCN4407 copy (32140989732) (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|280px|At the October 2016 Portugal AutoCl\u00e1ssico show, a racing version with full roll-cage and widened sports body was also shown]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite book | year = 1997 | title = Opel GT Projekt 1484 | author = Henrion/M\u00fcller | publisher = Podszun | isbn = 3-86133-170-5 }}\n*{{cite book | year = n.d. | title = Opel GT Gold Portfolio 1968\u20131973 | author = road test article compilation | publisher = Brooklands Books | isbn = 1-85520-326-X}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Opel GT}}\n* [http://www.opelclub.com/ Opel Motorsport Club]\n* [http://www.opelgt.com/ The Classic Opel Community]\